The '''Bureau for the Repression of Communist Activities''' ('''Buró para Represión de las Actividades Comunistas''', or '''BRAC''') was the [[Cuba]]n [[secret police]] agency that President [[Fulgencio Batista]] maintained in the 1950s, which gained a reputation for brutality in its fight against the [[26th of July Movement]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jonathanpollard.org/2000/021900b.htm |title=Miami Herald: Faget's father was a brutal Batista official |website=Jonathanpollard.org |date= |accessdate=2016-01-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geocities.com/theangryearth/batista.html |title=Bush and Batista: Brothers in Arms |author=Jean-Guy Allard |website=Webcitation.org |accessdate=2016-01-14 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5knpwo2zm?url=http://www.geocities.com/theangryearth/batista.html |archivedate=October 26, 2009 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latinamericanstudies.org/cuban-rebels/kirkpatrick.htm |title=Cuba's Batista |website=Latinamericanstudies.org |date=1959-01-01 |accessdate=2016-01-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themilitant.com/1996/6016/6016_13.html |title=4/22/96 - Camilo Cienfuegos As An Immigrant In U.S |publisher=The Militant |date= |accessdate=2016-01-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cubaverdad.net/revolution.htm |title=The Cuban revolution the truth behind the lies |website=Cubaverdad.net |date= |accessdate=2016-01-14}}</ref>
The bureau was headed by Mariano Faget, who had first gained fame as a Nazi hunter during Batista's first turn at power, from 1940 to 1944, when he was chief of the Office of Investigation of Enemy Activities (''Oficina de Investigación de Actividades Enemigas''),{{efn|Also called the ''Servicio'', ''Buró'' or ''Sección de Investigación de Actividades Enemigas''.}} a [[Counterintelligence|counter-espionage]] unit that targeted Nazi and Fascist agents.
Development of BRAC was aided and encouraged by the CIA starting in 1956.
